.SS "enif_alloc()"

.IP
.nf
void * enif_alloc(
        size_t size);

.fi

.PP
Allocates memory of \fIsize\fR bytes.

.PP
Returns \fINULL\fR if the allocation fails.

.PP
The returned pointer is suitably aligned for any built-in type that fit in the allocated memory.

.SS "enif_alloc_binary()"

.IP
.nf
int enif_alloc_binary(
        size_t size,
        ErlNifBinary* bin);

.fi

.PP
Allocates a new binary of size \fIsize\fR bytes. Initializes the structure pointed to by \fIbin\fR to refer to the allocated binary. The binary must either be released by \fIenif_release_binary\fR or ownership transferred to an Erlang term with \fIenif_make_binary\fR. An allocated (and owned) \fIErlNifBinary\fR can be kept between NIF calls.

.PP
If you do not need to reallocate or keep the data alive across NIF calls, consider using \fIenif_make_new_binary\fR instead as it will allocate small binaries on the process heap when possible.

.PP
Returns \fItrue\fR on success, or \fIfalse\fR if allocation fails.

.SS "enif_alloc_env()"

.IP
.nf
ErlNifEnv * enif_alloc_env();

.fi

.PP
Allocates a new process independent environment. The environment can be used to hold terms that are not bound to any process. Such terms can later be copied to a process environment with \fIenif_make_copy\fR or be sent to a process as a message with \fIenif_send\fR.

.PP
Returns pointer to the new environment.

.PP
Available since OTP R14B

